value.value: Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with the heterocyclic imidazole groups.
Indicates that a cross-linker is thioesterized.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with RNA or DNA.
An amino acid derivative used in cross-linking experiments.
A handle attached to a cross-linker used for detection, affinity enrichment or purification.
A Biotin affinity handle, enrichable with avidin, streptavidin or neutravidin, attached to a cross-linker.
A NO2 detection tag.

An alkyne (hadrocarbon with at least one C-C triple bond) tag, e.g. BARAC (biarylazacycloctynone) to enable enrichment of cross-linked peptides by either coupling of an affinity group with alkyne-azido click chemistry or by using immobilized azide linkers.
A dinitrobenzole affinity handle for enrichment with anti-DNB antibodies, attached to a cross-linker.

A photoreactive azide (-N3) tag to enable enrichment of cross-linked peptides with either immobilized alkyne linkers or by azide-alkyne click chemistry using biotin-alkyne respective biotin-phosphine.
An alpha-cyano-4-hydroxycinnamic acid UV-absorbing label for signal enhancement.
A generic neutral loss reporter.
An amino acid compound.
The amino acid L-Leucine.
The amino acid L-Methionine.
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by bases.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with hydrazines (N2H4).
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with carbonyl (R1-CO-R2) groups.
Indicates that a cross-linker is oxidized, e.g. by oxidizing a carbonyl to a carboxyl functional group.
Indicates that a cross-linker is modified to it's alkene form (loss of two hydrogen atoms by forming a C=C double bond).
Indicates that a cross-linker is chemically cleavable by acids.
Indicates that a cross-linker contains a CID (Collision Induced Dissociation) cleavable C-S bond.
The amino acid L-Isoleucine.
Indicates that a cross-linker is labelled with oxygen-18.
The amino acid L-Phenylalanine.
A Iminobiotin trifluoroacetamide affinity handle, enrichable with avidin, streptavidin or neutravidin, attached to a cross-linker.
Indicates that a reactive group is reactive with either of the glycoproteins avidin, streptavidin or neutravidin.
A nitrogeneous base occurring in nucleic acids.
A purine base occurring in nucleic acids.
A pyrimidine base occurring in nucleic acids.
The nucleobase adenine.
The nucleobase guanine.
The nucleobase cytosine.
The nucleobase thymine.
The nucleobase uracil.
A nucleobase derivative used in cross-linking experiments for protein-oligonucleotide cross-linking.
A combination of a nucleobase and a sugar (either ribose or deoxyribose).
The nucleoside adenosine.
The nucleoside guanosine.
The nucleoside cytidine.
The nucleoside uridine.
The nucleoside 5-methyluridine.
A nucleoside derivative used in cross-linking experiments for protein-oligonucleotide cross-linking.
Thiol-modified RNA.
A biotin-alkyne affinity handle, which can be used for enrichment with click-chemistry.
A tetramethylrhodamine-alkyne affinity handle, which can be used for enrichment with click-chemistry.
A lipid analogue used in cross-linking experiments for lipid-protein cross-linking.
A sialic acid analogue used in cross-linking experiments for glycan-protein cross-linking.
Alkenization dead-end modification resulting from a cross-linker reagent reacting only with one peptide.
